{"id":"1507.01385","submitter":"Kodai Wada","authors":"Kodai Wada, Akira Yasuhara","title":"The Milnor invariants of clover links","comments":"arXiv admin note: substantial text overlap with arXiv:1506.03922","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  J.P. Levine introduced a clover link to investigate the indeterminacy of the\nMilnor invariants of a link. It is shown that for a clover link, the Milnor\nnumbers of length at most $2k+1$ are well-defined if those of length at most\n$k$ vanish, and that the Milnor numbers of length at least $2k+2$ are not\nwell-defined if those of length $k+1$ survive. For a clover link $c$ with the\nMilnor numbers of length at most $k$ vanishing, we show that the Milnor number\n$\\mu_c(I)$ for a sequence $I$ is well-defined up to the greatest common devisor\nof $\\mu_{c}(J)'s$, where $J$ is a subsequence of $I$ obtained by removing at\nleast $k+1$ indices. Moreover, if $I$ is a non-repeated sequence with length\n$2k+2$, the possible range of $\\mu_c(I)$ is given explicitly. As an\napplication, we give an edge-homotopy classification of $4$-clover links.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 Jul 2015 10:52:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-07-07"}
{"id":"1507.01386","submitter":"Francisco Gancedo","authors":"Peter Constantin, Francisco Gancedo, Roman Shvydkoy and Vlad Vicol","title":"Global regularity for 2D Muskat equations with finite slope","comments":"32 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the 2D Muskat equation for the interface between two constant\ndensity fluids in an incompressible porous medium, with velocity given by\nDarcy's law. We establish that as long as the slope of the interface between\nthe two fluids remains bounded and uniformly continuous, the solution remains\nregular. The proofs exploit the nonlocal nonlinear parabolic nature of the\nequations through a series of nonlinear lower bounds for nonlocal operators.\nThese are used to deduce that as long as the slope of the interface remains\nuniformly bounded, the curvature remains bounded. The nonlinear bounds then\nallow us to obtain local existence for arbitrarily large initial data in the\nclass $W^{2,p}$, $1<p\\leq \\infty$. We provide furthermore a global regularity\nresult for small initial data: if the initial slope of the interface is\nsufficiently small, there exists a unique solution for all time.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 Jul 2015 11:06:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-07-07"}
